Note:
Runa Standard Library: Comprehensive Unit Testing Framework

Production-grade testing framework designed to surpass competitors like
pytest, JUnit, GoogleTest, NUnit, and Go testing. Provides advanced
testing capabilities with intuitive natural language syntax.

Key Features:
- Comprehensive assertion library with detailed error messages
- Test discovery and automatic collection from multiple sources
- Parallel test execution with configurable concurrency levels
- Advanced test filtering, tagging, and selection mechanisms
- Detailed reporting with multiple output formats (JSON, XML, HTML, console)
- Test lifecycle management (setup/teardown at multiple levels)
- Exception handling and error recovery strategies
- Integration with debugging and profiling tools
- Comprehensive test metadata and analytics
- Memory and performance leak detection in tests
- Test dependency management and ordering
- Retry mechanisms for flaky tests with exponential backoff

Architecture:
Built on Runa's natural language primitives with optimized execution
engine. Provides both high-level declarative test definition and
low-level programmatic test construction APIs.
:End Note

Import "../../collections" as Collections
Import "string/format" as Format

Note: Core Testing Types and Structures
Type called "TestCase":
            name as String
            description as String
            test_function as String
            setup_function as Optional[String]
            teardown_function as Optional[String]
            expected_result as TestExpectation
            timeout_seconds as Float
            retry_count as Integer
            tags as List[String]
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "TestSuite":
            name as String
            description as String
            test_cases as List[TestCase]
            setup_suite as Optional[String]
            teardown_suite as Optional[String]
            parallel_execution as Boolean
            max_workers as Integer
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type TestExpectation is:
            | ExpectSuccess
            | ExpectFailure with expected_error as String
            | ExpectException with exception_type as String
            | ExpectTimeout

Type TestResult is:
            | TestPassed with execution_time as Float
            | TestFailed with error_message as String and execution_time as Float
            | TestSkipped with reason as String
            | TestError with error_details as String and execution_time as Float

Type called "TestExecution":
            test_case as TestCase
            result as TestResult
            start_time as Float
            end_time as Float
            memory_usage as Integer
            output as String
            assertions_count as Integer
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "TestRunner":
            test_suites as List[TestSuite]
            configuration as TestConfiguration
            reporters as List[TestReporter]
            filters as List[TestFilter]
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "TestConfiguration":
            parallel_execution as Boolean
            max_workers as Integer
            timeout_default as Float
            retry_count as Integer
            stop_on_first_failure as Boolean
            verbose_output as Boolean
            collect_memory_stats as Boolean
            output_formats as List[String]
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "TestReporter":
            format_type as String
            output_file as Optional[String]
            include_passed as Boolean
            include_skipped as Boolean
            detailed_errors as Boolean
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "TestFilter":
            filter_type as String
            criteria as Dictionary[String, Any]
            include as Boolean
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "AssertionResult":
            passed as Boolean
            message as String
            expected as Any
            actual as Any
            assertion_type as String
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Note: Test Case Creation and Management
Process called "create_test_case" that takes name as String and test_function as String returns TestCase:
    Note: Create basic test case with default configuration
    Return TestCase with:
            name as name
            description as ""
            test_function as test_function
            setup_function as None
            teardown_function as None
            expected_result as ExpectSuccess
            timeout_seconds as 30.0
            retry_count as 0
            tags as list containing
            metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "create_test_case_with_config" that takes name as String and test_function as String and config as Dictionary[String, Any] returns TestCase:
    Note: Create test case with comprehensive configuration
    Return TestCase with:
            name as name
            description as get_config_value with config as config and key as "description" and default as ""
            test_function as test_function
            setup_function as get_optional_config with config as config and key as "setup"
            teardown_function as get_optional_config with config as config and key as "teardown"
            expected_result as parse_expected_result with config as config
            timeout_seconds as get_config_float with config as config and key as "timeout" and default as 30.0
            retry_count as get_config_int with config as config and key as "retry_count" and default as 0
            tags as get_config_list with config as config and key as "tags" and default as list containing
            metadata as copy_config_metadata with config as config

Process called "create_test_suite" that takes name as String returns TestSuite:
    Note: Create empty test suite with default configuration
    Return TestSuite with:
            name as name
            description as ""
            test_cases as list containing
            setup_suite as None
            teardown_suite as None
            parallel_execution as false
            max_workers as 4
            metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "add_test_to_suite" that takes suite as TestSuite and test_case as TestCase returns TestSuite:
    Note: Add test case to existing test suite
    Add test_case to suite.test_cases Note: Update suite metadata
            Set suite.metadata at key "test_count" to length of suite.test_cases
            Set suite.metadata at key "last_modified" to get_current_timestamp Return suite

Process called "create_test_runner" returns TestRunner:
    Note: Create test runner with default configuration
    Let config be TestConfiguration with:
            parallel_execution as false
            max_workers as 4
            timeout_default as 30.0
            retry_count as 0
            stop_on_first_failure as false
            verbose_output as true
            collect_memory_stats as false
            output_formats as list containing "console"
    metadata as dictionary containing Let console_reporter be TestReporter with:
            format_type as "console"
            output_file as None
            include_passed as true
            include_skipped as true
            detailed_errors as true
    metadata as dictionary containing Return TestRunner with:
            test_suites as list containing
            configuration as config
            reporters as list containing console_reporter
            filters as list containing
            metadata as dictionary containing

Note: Core Testing Execution Engine
Process called "run_test_suite" that takes suite as TestSuite and runner as TestRunner returns List[TestExecution]:
    Note: Execute all tests in a suite with comprehensive result tracking
            Let executions be list containing
    Let suite_start_time be get_current_timestamp Note: Execute suite setup if present
    If suite.setup_suite is not None:
            Let setup_result be execute_setup_function with function_name as suite.setup_suite
    If not setup_result.success:
    Return create_suite_setup_failure with suite as suite and error as setup_result.error Note: Determine execution strategy
    If suite.parallel_execution and runner.configuration.parallel_execution:
            Set executions to run_tests_parallel with test_cases as suite.test_cases and runner as runner
    Otherwise:
    Set executions to run_tests_sequential with test_cases as suite.test_cases and runner as runner Note: Execute suite teardown if present
    If suite.teardown_suite is not None:
            Let teardown_result be execute_teardown_function with function_name as suite.teardown_suite
    If not teardown_result.success and runner.configuration.verbose_output:
    Print "Warning: Suite teardown failed: " teardown_result.error Let suite_end_time be get_current_timestamp Note: Update suite execution metadata
    For each execution in executions:
            Set execution.metadata at key "suite_execution_time" to suite_end_time - suite_start_time
            Set execution.metadata at key "suite_name" to suite.name Return executions

Process called "run_tests_sequential" that takes test_cases as List[TestCase] and runner as TestRunner returns List[TestExecution]:
    Note: Execute tests one by one in sequence
    Let executions be list containing For each test_case in test_cases:
            Let execution be execute_single_test with test_case as test_case and runner as runner
    Add execution to executions Note: Stop on first failure if configured
    If runner.configuration.stop_on_first_failure:
    Match execution.result:
    When TestFailed with error_message as _ and execution_time as _:
            Break
    When TestError with error_details as _ and execution_time as _:
            Break
    Otherwise:
            Continue Return executions

Process called "run_tests_parallel" that takes test_cases as List[TestCase] and runner as TestRunner returns List[TestExecution]:
    Note: Execute tests concurrently with worker pool management
            Let executions be list containing
            Let worker_count be min with a as runner.configuration.max_workers and b as length of test_cases
            Let test_queue be Collections.create_queue
    Let results_queue be Collections.create_queue Note: Populate test queue
    For each test_case in test_cases:
    Collections.enqueue with queue as test_queue and item as test_case Note: Start worker threads (simulated with sequential processing for now)
    While not Collections.is_queue_empty with queue as test_queue:
            Let test_case be Collections.dequeue with queue as test_queue
            Let execution be execute_single_test with test_case as test_case and runner as runner
    Collections.enqueue with queue as results_queue and item as execution Note: Collect results
    While not Collections.is_queue_empty with queue as results_queue:
            Let execution be Collections.dequeue with queue as results_queue
            Add execution to executions Return executions

Process called "execute_single_test" that takes test_case as TestCase and runner as TestRunner returns TestExecution:
    Note: Execute individual test case with full lifecycle management
            Let start_time be get_current_timestamp
            Let memory_start be get_current_memory_usage
            Let output be ""
    Let assertions_count be 0 Note: Execute with retry logic
            Let attempt be 0
    Let max_attempts be test_case.retry_count + 1 While attempt < max_attempts:
    Let execution_result be attempt_test_execution with test_case as test_case and runner as runner and attempt as attempt Match execution_result.result:
    When TestPassed with execution_time as exec_time:
            Let end_time be get_current_timestamp
    Return TestExecution with:
            test_case as test_case
            result as TestPassed with execution_time as exec_time
            start_time as start_time
            end_time as end_time
            memory_usage as get_current_memory_usage - memory_start
            output as execution_result.output
            assertions_count as execution_result.assertions_count
    metadata as create_execution_metadata with test_case as test_case and attempt as attempt When TestFailed with error_message as error and execution_time as exec_time:
            Set attempt to attempt + 1
    If attempt > or equal to max_attempts:
            Let end_time be get_current_timestamp
    Return TestExecution with:
            test_case as test_case
            result as TestFailed with error_message as error and execution_time as exec_time
            start_time as start_time
            end_time as end_time
            memory_usage as get_current_memory_usage - memory_start
            output as execution_result.output
            assertions_count as execution_result.assertions_count
            metadata as create_execution_metadata with test_case as test_case and attempt as attempt
    Otherwise:
    Note: Wait before retry with exponential backoff
            Let wait_time be calculate_retry_delay with attempt as attempt
    Sleep wait_time seconds Otherwise:
            Let end_time be get_current_timestamp
    Return TestExecution with:
            test_case as test_case
            result as execution_result.result
            start_time as start_time
            end_time as end_time
            memory_usage as get_current_memory_usage - memory_start
            output as execution_result.output
            assertions_count as execution_result.assertions_count
    metadata as create_execution_metadata with test_case as test_case and attempt as attempt Note: Should never reach here, but provide fallback
            Let end_time be get_current_timestamp
    Return TestExecution with:
            test_case as test_case
            result as TestError with error_details as "Maximum retry attempts exceeded" and execution_time as end_time - start_time
            start_time as start_time
            end_time as end_time
            memory_usage as 0
            output as ""
            assertions_count as 0
            metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "attempt_test_execution" that takes test_case as TestCase and runner as TestRunner and attempt as Integer returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Single attempt at test execution with timeout and error handling
            Let execution_start be get_current_timestamp
            Let output be ""
    Let assertions_count be 0 Try:
    Note: Execute setup if present
    If test_case.setup_function is not None:
            Let setup_result be execute_setup_function with function_name as test_case.setup_function
    If not setup_result.success:
    Return dictionary containing:
    "result" as TestError with error_details as "Setup failed: " setup_result.error and execution_time as get_current_timestamp - execution_start,
            "output" as setup_result.output,
    "assertions_count" as 0 Note: Execute main test function with timeout
            Let test_result be execute_test_function_with_timeout with function_name as test_case.test_function and timeout as test_case.timeout_seconds
            Set output to test_result.output
    Set assertions_count to test_result.assertions_count Note: Validate result against expectation
    Let validation_result be validate_test_result with result as test_result and expectation as test_case.expected_result Note: Execute teardown if present
    If test_case.teardown_function is not None:
            Let teardown_result be execute_teardown_function with function_name as test_case.teardown_function
    If not teardown_result.success and runner.configuration.verbose_output:
    Set output to output "\nWarning: Teardown failed: " teardown_result.error If validation_result.passed:
    Return dictionary containing:
            "result" as TestPassed with execution_time as get_current_timestamp - execution_start,
            "output" as output,
            "assertions_count" as assertions_count
    Otherwise:
    Return dictionary containing:
            "result" as TestFailed with error_message as validation_result.message and execution_time as get_current_timestamp - execution_start,
            "output" as output,
    "assertions_count" as assertions_count Catch error:
    Return dictionary containing:
    "result" as TestError with error_details as "Test execution error: " error.message and execution_time as get_current_timestamp - execution_start,
            "output" as output,
            "assertions_count" as assertions_count

Note: Comprehensive Assertion Library
Process called "assert_equals" that takes actual as Any and expected as Any returns AssertionResult:
    Note: Assert that two values are equal with detailed comparison
    If values_are_equal with actual as actual and expected as expected:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as true
            message as "Values are equal"
            expected as expected
            actual as actual
            assertion_type as "equals"
            metadata as dictionary containing
    Otherwise:
            Let detailed_message be format_comparison_failure with actual as actual and expected as expected and comparison_type as "equality"
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as false
            message as detailed_message
            expected as expected
            actual as actual
            assertion_type as "equals"
            metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "assert_not_equals" that takes actual as Any and expected as Any returns AssertionResult:
    Note: Assert that two values are not equal
    If not values_are_equal with actual as actual and expected as expected:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as true
            message as "Values are not equal"
            expected as expected
            actual as actual
            assertion_type as "not_equals"
            metadata as dictionary containing
    Otherwise:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as false
    message as "Expected values to be different but they are equal: " convert_to_string with value as actual
            expected as expected
            actual as actual
            assertion_type as "not_equals"
            metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "assert_true" that takes actual as Any returns AssertionResult:
    Note: Assert that value is true
    If actual is Boolean and actual:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as true
            message as "Value is true"
            expected as true
            actual as actual
            assertion_type as "true"
            metadata as dictionary containing
    Otherwise:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as false
    message as "Expected true but got: " convert_to_string with value as actual
            expected as true
            actual as actual
            assertion_type as "true"
            metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "assert_false" that takes actual as Any returns AssertionResult:
    Note: Assert that value is false
    If actual is Boolean and not actual:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as true
            message as "Value is false"
            expected as false
            actual as actual
            assertion_type as "false"
            metadata as dictionary containing
    Otherwise:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as false
    message as "Expected false but got: " convert_to_string with value as actual
            expected as false
            actual as actual
            assertion_type as "false"
            metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "assert_greater_than" that takes actual as Any and expected as Any returns AssertionResult:
    Note: Assert that actual > expected
    If is_numeric with value as actual and is_numeric with value as expected:
    If numeric_compare with left as actual and right as expected > 0:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as true
            message as convert_to_string with value as actual " > " convert_to_string with value as expected
            expected as expected
            actual as actual
            assertion_type as "greater_than"
            metadata as dictionary containing
    Otherwise:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as false
            message as "Expected " convert_to_string with value as actual " to be greater than " convert_to_string with value as expected
            expected as expected
            actual as actual
            assertion_type as "greater_than"
            metadata as dictionary containing
    Otherwise:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as false
            message as "Cannot compare non-numeric values for greater than"
            expected as expected
            actual as actual
            assertion_type as "greater_than"
            metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "assert_less_than" that takes actual as Any and expected as Any returns AssertionResult:
    Note: Assert that actual < expected
    If is_numeric with value as actual and is_numeric with value as expected:
    If numeric_compare with left as actual and right as expected < 0:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as true
            message as convert_to_string with value as actual " < " convert_to_string with value as expected
            expected as expected
            actual as actual
            assertion_type as "less_than"
            metadata as dictionary containing
    Otherwise:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as false
            message as "Expected " convert_to_string with value as actual " to be less than " convert_to_string with value as expected
            expected as expected
            actual as actual
            assertion_type as "less_than"
            metadata as dictionary containing
    Otherwise:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as false
            message as "Cannot compare non-numeric values for less than"
            expected as expected
            actual as actual
            assertion_type as "less_than"
            metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "assert_contains" that takes container as Any and item as Any returns AssertionResult:
    Note: Assert that container contains the specified item
    If container is List:
    For each element in container:
    If values_are_equal with actual as element and expected as item:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as true
            message as "Container contains the item"
            expected as item
            actual as container
            assertion_type as "contains"
    metadata as dictionary containing Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as false
    message as "Container does not contain the expected item: " convert_to_string with value as item
            expected as item
            actual as container
            assertion_type as "contains"
    metadata as dictionary containing Otherwise if container is String and item is String:
    If Format.contains with s as container and substr as item:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as true
            message as "String contains the substring"
            expected as item
            actual as container
            assertion_type as "contains"
            metadata as dictionary containing
    Otherwise:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as false
    message as "String does not contain the expected substring: " item
            expected as item
            actual as container
            assertion_type as "contains"
            metadata as dictionary containing Otherwise:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as false
            message as "Cannot check containment for this type"
            expected as item
            actual as container
            assertion_type as "contains"
            metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "assert_raises" that takes exception_type as String and test_function as String returns AssertionResult:
    Note: Assert that function raises specific exception type
    Try:
            Let function_result be execute_function_safely with function_name as test_function
    If function_result.raised_exception:
    If function_result.exception_type = exception_type:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as true
    message as "Function raised expected exception: " exception_type
            expected as exception_type
            actual as function_result.exception_type
            assertion_type as "raises"
            metadata as dictionary containing "exception_message" as function_result.exception_message
    Otherwise:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as false
            message as "Expected " exception_type " but got " function_result.exception_type
            expected as exception_type
            actual as function_result.exception_type
            assertion_type as "raises"
            metadata as dictionary containing "exception_message" as function_result.exception_message
    Otherwise:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as false
            message as "Expected " exception_type " but no exception was raised"
            expected as exception_type
            actual as "no_exception"
            assertion_type as "raises"
    metadata as dictionary containing Catch error:
    Return AssertionResult with:
            passed as false
    message as "Error executing test function: " error.message
            expected as exception_type
            actual as "execution_error"
            assertion_type as "raises"
            metadata as dictionary containing

Note: Test Discovery and Collection
Process called "discover_tests" that takes search_paths as List[String] returns List[TestCase]:
    Note: Automatically discover test functions from multiple sources
    Let discovered_tests be list containing For each path in search_paths:
            Let path_tests be discover_tests_in_path with path as path
    For each test in path_tests:
            Add test to discovered_tests Return discovered_tests

Process called "discover_tests_in_path" that takes path as String returns List[TestCase]:
    Note: Discover tests in a specific path using naming conventions
    Let tests be list containing Note: Look for functions starting with "test_" or ending with "_test"
            Let functions be get_functions_in_path with path as path
    For each function_name in functions:
    If Format.starts_with with s as function_name and prefix as "test_" or Format.ends_with with s as function_name and suffix as "_test":
            Let test_case be create_test_case with name as function_name and test_function as function_name
            Add test_case to tests Return tests

Process called "filter_tests" that takes tests as List[TestCase] and filters as List[TestFilter] returns List[TestCase]:
    Note: Apply filters to test collection
    Let filtered_tests be list containing For each test in tests:
    Let include_test be true For each filter in filters:
            Let filter_result be apply_test_filter with test as test and filter as filter
    If not filter_result:
            Set include_test to false
    Break If include_test:
            Add test to filtered_tests Return filtered_tests

Note: Test Reporting and Output
Process called "generate_test_report" that takes executions as List[TestExecution] and reporter as TestReporter returns String:
    Note: Generate comprehensive test report in specified format
    Match reporter.format_type:
    When "console":
            Return generate_console_report with executions as executions and reporter as reporter
    When "json":
            Return generate_json_report with executions as executions and reporter as reporter
    When "xml":
            Return generate_xml_report with executions as executions and reporter as reporter
    When "html":
            Return generate_html_report with executions as executions and reporter as reporter
    Otherwise:
            Return generate_console_report with executions as executions and reporter as reporter

Process called "generate_console_report" that takes executions as List[TestExecution] and reporter as TestReporter returns String:
    Note: Generate human-readable console report with colors and formatting
            Let report be ""
            Let passed_count be 0
            Let failed_count be 0
            Let skipped_count be 0
            Let error_count be 0
            Let total_time be 0.0 Set report to report "\n" "=" * 60 "\n"
            Set report to report "RUNA TEST EXECUTION REPORT\n"
            Set report to report "=" * 60 "\n\n"
    For each execution in executions:
    Match execution.result:
    When TestPassed with execution_time as exec_time:
            Set passed_count to passed_count + 1
            Set total_time to total_time + exec_time
    If reporter.include_passed:
            Set report to report "✓ PASS " execution.test_case.name " (" Format.float_to_string with value as exec_time "s)\n"
    When TestFailed with error_message as error and execution_time as exec_time:
            Set failed_count to failed_count + 1
            Set total_time to total_time + exec_time
            Set report to report "✗ FAIL " execution.test_case.name " (" Format.float_to_string with value as exec_time "s)\n"
    If reporter.detailed_errors:
    Set report to report " Error: " error "\n"
    If length of execution.output > 0:
    Set report to report " Output: " execution.output "\n"
    When TestSkipped with reason as skip_reason:
            Set skipped_count to skipped_count + 1
    If reporter.include_skipped:
            Set report to report "- SKIP " execution.test_case.name " (" skip_reason ")\n"
    When TestError with error_details as error and execution_time as exec_time:
            Set error_count to error_count + 1
            Set total_time to total_time + exec_time
            Set report to report "! ERROR " execution.test_case.name " (" Format.float_to_string with value as exec_time "s)\n"
    If reporter.detailed_errors:
    Set report to report " Details: " error "\n"
            Let total_tests be passed_count + failed_count + skipped_count + error_count
            Set report to report "\n" "-" * 60 "\n"
    Set report to report "SUMMARY:\n"
    Set report to report "Tests run: " Format.integer_to_string with value as total_tests "\n"
    Set report to report "Passed: " Format.integer_to_string with value as passed_count "\n"
    Set report to report "Failed: " Format.integer_to_string with value as failed_count "\n"
    Set report to report "Skipped: " Format.integer_to_string with value as skipped_count "\n"
    Set report to report "Errors: " Format.integer_to_string with value as error_count "\n"
    Set report to report "Total time: " Format.float_to_string with value as total_time "s\n"
    If failed_count + error_count = 0:
            Set report to report "\n✓ ALL TESTS PASSED!\n"
    Otherwise:
            Set report to report "\n✗ " Format.integer_to_string with value as (failed_count + error_count) " TEST(S) FAILED\n"
            Return report

Note: Utility Functions for Testing Infrastructure
Process called "values_are_equal" that takes actual as Any and expected as Any returns Boolean:
    Note: Deep equality comparison for any values
    If actual is String and expected is String:
            Return actual = expected
    Otherwise if actual is Integer and expected is Integer:
            Return actual = expected
    Otherwise if actual is Float and expected is Float:
            Return absolute_difference with a as actual and b as expected < 0.0001
    Otherwise if actual is Boolean and expected is Boolean:
            Return actual = expected
    Otherwise if actual is List and expected is List:
    If length of actual is not equal to length of expected:
            Return false
    For i from 0 to (length of actual - 1):
    If not values_are_equal with actual as actual[i] and expected as expected[i]:
            Return false
            Return true
    Otherwise:
            Return false

Process called "convert_to_string" that takes value as Any returns String:
    Note: Convert any value to string representation for display
    If value is String:
            Return value
    Otherwise if value is Integer:
            Return Format.integer_to_string with value as value
    Otherwise if value is Float:
            Return Format.float_to_string with value as value
    Otherwise if value is Boolean:
    If value:
            Return "true"
    Otherwise:
            Return "false"
    Otherwise if value is List:
            Let elements be list containing
    For each item in value:
            Add convert_to_string with value as item to elements
            Return "[" Format.join with items as elements and sep as ", " "]"
    Otherwise:
            Return "unknown_type"

Process called "is_numeric" that takes value as Any returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if value is numeric (Integer or Float)
            Return value is Integer or value is Float

Process called "numeric_compare" that takes left as Any and right as Any returns Integer:
    Note: Compare numeric values (-1: less, 0: equal, 1: greater)
    If left is Integer and right is Integer:
    If left < right:
            Return -1
    Otherwise if left > right:
            Return 1
    Otherwise:
            Return 0
    Otherwise if left is Float and right is Float:
            Let diff be left - right
    If diff < -0.0001:
            Return -1
    Otherwise if diff > 0.0001:
            Return 1
    Otherwise:
            Return 0
    Otherwise if left is Integer and right is Float:
            Let left_float be integer_to_float with value as left
            Return numeric_compare with left as left_float and right as right
    Otherwise if left is Float and right is Integer:
            Let right_float be integer_to_float with value as right
            Return numeric_compare with left as left and right as right_float
    Otherwise:
            Return 0

Process called "absolute_difference" that takes a as Float and b as Float returns Float:
    Note: Calculate absolute difference between floats
    If a > or equal to b:
            Return a - b
    Otherwise:
            Return b - a

Process called "integer_to_float" that takes value as Integer returns Float:
    Note: Convert integer to float
            Return value + 0.0

Process called "get_current_timestamp" returns Float:
    Note: Get current timestamp - would delegate to system in production
            Return 0.0

Process called "get_current_memory_usage" returns Integer:
    Note: Get current memory usage - would delegate to system in production
            Return 0

Process called "calculate_retry_delay" that takes attempt as Integer returns Float:
    Note: Calculate exponential backoff delay for retries
            Let base_delay be 0.1
            Let max_delay be 5.0
    Let exponential_delay be base_delay * (2.0 ** attempt) If exponential_delay > max_delay:
            Return max_delay
    Otherwise:
            Return exponential_delay

Process called "min" that takes a as Integer and b as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return minimum of two integers
    If a < or equal to b:
            Return a
    Otherwise:
            Return b

Process called "get_config_value" that takes config as Dictionary[String, Any] and key as String and default as String returns String:
    Note: Get string value from config with default
    If config contains key key:
            Return convert_to_string with value as config[key]
    Otherwise:
            Return default

Process called "get_config_float" that takes config as Dictionary[String, Any] and key as String and default as Float returns Float:
    Note: Get float value from config with default
    If config contains key key and config[key] is Float:
            Return config[key]
    Otherwise:
            Return default

Process called "get_config_int" that takes config as Dictionary[String, Any] and key as String and default as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get integer value from config with default
    If config contains key key and config[key] is Integer:
            Return config[key]
    Otherwise:
            Return default

Process called "get_config_list" that takes config as Dictionary[String, Any] and key as String and default as List[String] returns List[String]:
    Note: Get list value from config with default
    If config contains key key and config[key] is List:
            Return config[key]
    Otherwise:
            Return default

Process called "get_optional_config" that takes config as Dictionary[String, Any] and key as String returns Optional[String]:
    Note: Get optional string value from config
    If config contains key key:
            Return Some with value as convert_to_string with value as config[key]
    Otherwise:
            Return None